               <p>THOMAS BUMPUS. I live at <placeName id="t18260406-321-crimeloc1718">Holborn-bars</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260406-321-crimeloc1718" type="placeName" value="Holborn-bars"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260406-321-crimeloc1718" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260406-321-off1716 t18260406-321-crimeloc1718"></join>, in the City. I am a <rs id="t18260406-321-viclabel1719" type="occupation">bookseller</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260406-321-victim1715 t18260406-321-viclabel1719"></join> - this book is mine; I had seen it safe about twelve o'clock on the 1st of April.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260406-321-person1716">
                  JOSEPH 
                  NICHOLSON
               <interp inst="t18260406-321-person1716" type="surname" value="NICHOLSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260406-321-person1716" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260406-321-person1716" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am porter at the Blue Posts public-house. On the 1st of April Mrs. Bumpus called to me, about ten minutes past two o'clock, to go after the prisoner - she gave me his description; I found him in Middle-row, looking into a bookseller's shop; I brought him back, and found this book in his right hand coat pocket.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I cannot say I am not guilty, but the officer can tell you I was in a desperate state of madness, occasioned by a kick of a horse over my eye; I had drank some liquor that day; I was tied down in a straight waistcoat for thirty hours in convulsive fits in consequence of what I had done.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 23.</p>
